<DOC><DOCNO> AP880601-0332 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-01-88 2131EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Mazda-FlatRock     06-01 0174</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Mazda-Flat Rock,0180</SECOND><HEAD>Mazda Adds Second Shift at Flat Rock Plant</HEAD><DATELINE>FLAT ROCK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mazda Motor Corp. has added a secondproduction shift as scheduled at its U.S. assembly plant in FlatRock, a company spokesman said Wednesday.   The 1,300-worker second shift began work Tuesday, boostingmonthly production of Ford Probe and Mazda MX-6 coupes to 13,000cars a month in June from 9,600 a month in May, spokesman AtsuoKatada said.   The $550 million plant employs 2,600 hourly workers and 550salaried workers on two shifts. When it reaches full production inAugust, it will be building 240,000 cars a year.   The plant began production in September. More than 60 percent ofits production is devoted to the Probe, which is sold through Forddealers exclusively and has attracted so many dealer orders it issold out through October.   Katada said Mazda has no plans to expand the factory or increaseits annual capacity beyond 240,000 vehicles despite Japanesenewspaper reports that it will build 300,000 cars a year there.</TEXT></DOC>